<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / UK Company News: Ellis &amp; Everard declines 29%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ELLIS &amp; EVERARD, the chemicals distribution company, yesterday reported its
first profits decline in 10 years, with the interim return down 29 per cent
to Pounds 7.5m.
Mr Peter Wood, managing director, warned that conditions continued to be
difficult in the second half, and said it was likely that the group would
report lower profits for the full year.
'We assume that the underlying level of demand will remain depressed for the
remainder of the financial year,' he said.
The impact of the recession on the group's non-core, higher margin
businesses - swimming pool chemicals and surface cleaning products  - took
the heaviest toll. These operations accounted for about Pounds 1.5m of the
overall Pounds 3m decline in profits.
The US, where operating profits fell by about 24 per cent, accounted for a
further Pounds 1m of the pre-tax decline. The remaining profit fall was due
to losses of about Pounds 400,000 at the Spanish operations.
Mr Michael Marshall, chairman, said the group had concentrated on reducing
costs in the first half and had maintained them virtually at 1990 levels.
This would imply that Pounds 1.5m had been trimmed from total costs - before
acquisitions, said Mr Wood. Some 5 per cent of jobs had also been cut.
Mr Wood stressed that the performance of the core UK commodity chemicals
businesses had proved the group's long-held maxim that distribution
companies benefited in times of recession. The theory is that customers will
switch to buying smaller quantities from distributors rather than in bulk
from manufacturers.
In the UK, profits declined by just 2 per cent, he said. In the US, chemical
distributors form a larger share of the overall chemicals market, and thus
do not benefit as much from an economic downturn.
Acquisitions, which were largely responsible for the 10 per cent increase in
group sales to Pounds 198m, contributed little to profits.
Mr Wood said the group saw its future growth and focus in the 'heartland
commodity chemicals business'. However, he would not be drawn on whether the
group intended to put the non-core businesses up for sale.
Interest charges rose from Pounds 200,000 to Pounds 1m. Mr Wood said debt -
about Pounds 16m at the half year, or 25 per cent geared  - would be reduced
by the year-end. Earnings per share fell by 30 per cent to 6.7p. The interim
dividend is held at 2.25p.
COMMENT
It looks like this will be a dull year for Ellis &amp; Everard. At least the
declines of the second half have been halted. The group appears to be
bumping along the bottom - a condition it might be able to maintain for some
time yet. Ellis &amp; Everard has maintained its market share and simply has
along with everyone else. Forecasts for the full year are pitched at Pounds
14m, making a prospective p/e of about 15. This looks a little high for the
moment, given the economic uncertainty.
</TEXT>
