<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / Demand for credit shrinks as consumers repay debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RELUCTANCE of British consumers to borrow, reflected in official figures
released yesterday, underlines expectations of a slow economic recovery.
Demand for credit shrank in the three months to November, when consumers
made a net repayment of Pounds 216m.
This compared with net borrowings of Pounds 183m in the previous three
months.
In November, the latest monthly figure available, consumers made a net
repayment of Pounds 33m on credit agreements with finance houses, building
societies, and on bank credit cards that are part of the Visa or Mastercard
system. This followed a net repayment of Pounds 76m in October.
According to the seasonally adjusted figures from the Central Statistical
Office, November was the fourth successive month in which consumers made a
net repayment.
The previous increase in outstanding credit was in July when consumers added
Pounds 187m to their overall debts.
The amount of new credit advanced to consumers in November was Pounds 3.74bn
 -the lowest since June. In October new credit advanced was Pounds 4bn.
Consumers, chastened by rising unemployment and high interest rates, appear
to be making the repayment of expensive debts accrued in the 1980s a
priority.
Although the low credit figures are bad news for the government, which is
hoping for a consumer-led recovery, government ministers will have been
heartened by a small upwards revision in retail sales volumes for November.
Revised figures for retail sales in November, seasonally adjusted, showed a
1.3 per cent increase on October. However, in the three months to November
the volume of retail sales was down 0.3 per cent on the previous three
months.
Household goods, which are particularly sensitive indicators of consumer
confidence, were down 2 per cent on the previous three months, while
clothing and footwear were down by 3 per cent.
Lack of consumer confidence was further highlighted by the figures for
credit card debt where the amount outstanding increased by Pounds 50m in
November against Pounds 69m in October.
In the three months to November the amount outstanding increased by only
Pounds 45m, compared with an increase of Pounds 173m in the previous three
months.
Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist for Salomon Brothers International in
London, said he expected to see the emphasis on paying off debts continue
into this year.
'Consumer spending is being maintained by the run down of personal sector
bank deposits rather than through increased borrowing,' he said.
Mr John Shepperd, an economist at SG Warburg Securities, said economists
were taking a very cautious view of consumer spending, and consequently
revising their GDP forecasts downwards.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
