<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / EC farm stance seen as biggest threat to Gatt talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European Community objections to the draft agreement on farm subsidies
reform proposed last month may still wreck the Uruguay Round of trade talks.
Countries taking part in the trade liberalisation talks yesterday
unanimously agreed to work for successful completion of the talks by Easter.
But the EC is still opposed to the draft agreement on farm trade reform -
the most crucial of the 26 draft accords concluded last month.
The draft was prepared by Mr Arthur Dunkel, director-general of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt), after the US and the EC failed to
reach agreement following weeks of intensive talks. The Community's stance
is seen by negotiators as by far the most threatening.
The EC was not entirely without support at yesterday's meeting of the
top-level Trade Negotiations Committee (TNC) called to decide the future of
the five-year-old round. Japan, South Korea, Canada and Switzerland were
among participants also expressing serious reservations about proposals in
the agriculture text.
Mr Dunkel, who is also chairman of the TNC, said he was prepared to serve as
'honest broker' in the resolution of outstanding differences. He warned,
however, that any move to adjust the 436-page text 'must be very precise and
concentrated entirely on what we all can collectively agree to without
unravelling the package'.
'I have no new - or better - solutions to offer on my own,' he added.
President Bush of the US said yesterday that he was not pessimistic about
the chances of reaching a Gatt agreement, but he vowed to reject any deal on
global trading rules which failed to lower farm subsidies in Europe. At a
meeting with leaders of the American Farm Bureau Federation in Kansas City,
he said he would not take to the Congress a deal that was silent on
agriculture or unfavourable to American farmers.
In a deliberately low-key statement, Mr Tran van Thinh, head of the EC
delegation in Geneva, said the Community had serious difficulties with the
agriculture text - which would have to be 'significantly improved'. It was
also unhappy about some aspects of the rule-making accords. But the EC was
ready to continue negotiations on the basis of Mr Dunkel's proposed
timetable.
There remain serious doubts over whether other countries will be prepared to
reopen the farm subsidy talks as the Community wants.
The US and most members of 14-strong Cairns Group of farm exporters are
backing the current draft. If anything, they would like tighter disciplines.
Mr Rufus Yerxa, US ambassador to Gatt, said the draft final agreement
contained the basic ingredients for finalising the round, even though in
places it did not go as far as Washington would have liked.
Japan fears, Page 3
S Korean exports, Page 15
</TEXT>
