<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont keeps option of tax cuts -
Budget speculation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS signalled yesterday that the option of a tax-cutting pre-election
Budget remained firmly open as the Labour party sought to maintain its
attack on the government's management of the economy.
As Mr Tom King, the defence secretary, switched the emphasis of Conservative
campaigning to Labour's defence policy ahead of today's debate in the
Commons, ministers dismissed reports that the shape of the Budget had
already been decided.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, has yet to take any firm decisions on the
main measures that will be included.
Instead he is understood to be ready to keep open until a week or so before
the Budget the option of a cut in the basic rate of income tax or a large
increase in tax thresholds.
Mr Lamont's colleagues acknowledge strong pressure within the Conservative
party for a Budget that highlights the sharp difference between the
government and Labour's taxation policies.
For many, that points to a 1p cut in the basic rate of tax to present the
electorate with a stark choice in an April or May election.
In spite of Labour's 5-point lead in the latest opinion poll, ministers
believe that their attack over the past week on the opposition's plans for
the 'biggest tax increase in peacetime history' has put Mr Neil Kinnock on
the defen-sive.
The chancellor is said to be instinctively in favour of a reduction in the
basic rate as opposed to higher thresholds if the money can be found to
reduce taxation. In the past, however, Mr John Major, the prime minister,
has indicated that he prefers raising thresholds because of the help that
gives to those on the lower end of the income scale.
The final decision, however, will depend on the shape of the economy in the
weeks immediately preceding the Budget. Ministers believe that if the
recovery still looks weak, the pressure for tax cuts will be irresistible.
If, however, there is much stronger evidence of an upturn as sterling
stabilises, the chancellor will have to balance the possibility of lower
taxes against the potential for a pre-election cut in interest rates.
Labour meanwhile continued to insist that a tax-cutting Budget would provide
further evidence of the Conservatives' 'boom-bust' approach to economic
management. Speaking during one the regional tours that have marked the
launch of the Labour election campaign, Mr John Smith, the shadow
chancellor, repeated his party's call for a Budget for industry.
</TEXT>
