<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / Choice of Tees port purchaser defended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TEES &amp; Hartlepool Port Authority yesterday released the text of a letter
to employees defending its decision to sell the port to a consortium called
Teesside Holdings for Pounds 180m.
Mr John Peart, the authority's chairman, said the time had come for him to
make the board's position 'perfectly clear to those people who matter most,
its management and employees'.
The authority's decision to sell the port to Teesside Holdings has brought
bitter protests from the management-employee buy-out team which had
submitted a rival bid of Pounds 150m during the privatisation process.
Also objecting to the port's decision is Maritime Transport Services,
operator of the Thamesport container terminal on the Isle of Grain in Kent,
which outbid Teesside Holdings with an offer of Pounds 210m.
Mr Peart said in his letter to employees that some of the critics of the
sale procedure had opposed privatisation from the outset and others were
motivated by the need for publicity.
He said: 'Teesside Holdings was selected by the board of the authority as
the preferred bidder because its bid met most closely the privatisation
objectives set by the board and agreed with the secretary of state for
transport.
'These objectives have remained constant and uppermost in the board's
consideration throughout the privatisation process.
'Teesside Holdings' bid was particularly impressive in respect of the most
important of these objectives, maintaining the port as a separate,
Teesside-based company, protecting the the authority's assets and ensuring
that cash generated continues to be wholly devoted to the further
development of the local port facilities and projects benefiting the local
economy and community.'
Mr Peart's letter comes as Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the transport secretary,
prepares to announce whether he is prepared to approve the port authority's
decision. Earlier he had said he was 'minded' to do so.
The issue will come up in the Commons today when MPs are asked to approve an
order providing for the government to claw back a proportion of any property
profits made by any of the trust ports after privatisation. Government
business managers are expected to ensure a favourable vote.
Teesside Holdings is a three-way venture between Powell Duffryn, the quoted
engineering and shipping group, Humberside Holdings, a company jointly owned
by Powell Duffryn and private interests in the Humberside area, and
Investors in Industry, the venture capital group.
Mr Peart said Teesside Holdings had 'positive and immediate' proposals for
the development of the port and port-related facilities.
They comprised substantial capital investment in excess of that proposed by
the other bidders for the development of the port business and new storage
and distribution ventures.
Editorial comment, Page 14
</TEXT>
