<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / Auditors' subscription may rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANTS in England and Wales may face substantial increases in
subscriptions but gain greater access to the workings of their professional
association under plans for long-term reform, it emerged yesterday.
The council of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales
proposed a Pounds 15 rise in the annual subscription for 1993 to Pounds 100
for members in the European Community of at least five years' standing, and
a further increase of 12.5 per cent above inflation for the next two years.
The council voted in favour of greater openness in the institute's operation
and the provision of a range of new services at its annual conference in
Birmingham at the weekend.
Mr Andrew Colquhoun, secretary and chief executive, said last night the
council voted unanimously that it would recommend raising subscription
levels at a special meeting for members on June 2 this year.
He said the increase was essential to compensate for the effects of the
recession on institute's commercial activities, such as publication sales.
The institute had a pre-tax deficit of Pounds 633,000 for the year to
December 31 1990. He said unaudited figures for 1991 showed a loss of Pounds
200,000, and the 1992 budget estimates a further Pounds 500,000 loss
including a Pounds 300,000 contingency item.
The council approved a report on openness that would involve far greater
access to institute meetings, more representation and wider circulation of
documents of public interest.
It discussed long-term objectives that might include more lobbying and
advisory services for members, with emphasis on maintaining and promoting
the image of the chartered accountancy qualification.
</TEXT>
