<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / Privatisation of big ports sails into a storm: The fierce
controversy generated by the government's disposal programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   IT must have seemed a good idea to the government
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
inject a bit more competition into the ports industry and line the
Exchequer's pockets at the same time.
The plan was to privatise the 15 biggest of the 111 British ports that are
run neither by local authorities nor the private sector, but by
self-governing trusts set up under acts of parliament.
It should have attracted little controversy. Most of the ports were expected
to be quietly snapped up by management-employee buy-out teams rather than
speculative bidders - safeguards were built into the scheme to prevent the
ports from being turned into shopping malls. Yet the privatisation has
turned into an embarrassing political debacle.
Tomorrow the row will come to a head in the Commons when MPs are asked to
approve the first privatisation - the sale of Tees &amp; Hartlepool, Britain's
second-biggest cargo port, to the Teesside Holdings consortium.
Tees &amp; Hartlepool had been a founder member of the pro-privatisation club.
Like several trust ports, it was run by a management keen to take an equity
stake in a business freed from the straitjacket of trust status, which
prevented its expansion into related activities such as distribution and
property development.
There was, however, a catch. Under the privatisation legislation - the Ports
Act 1991 - the management could not simply take the port over. To ensure
best value for money for the taxpayer, the port had to be sold through a
competitive tender refereed by the non-executive members of the trust.
Proceeds would be split 50-50 between the port and the government.
When the trust came to take its decision last month, it had to choose
between four bids. The highest was Pounds 210m from Maritime Transport
Services, owner of the Thamesport container terminal in Kent. Next was
Pounds 180m from Teesside Holdings, a consortium comprising the Powell
Duffryn industrial group, venture capital group 3i, and private interests in
the Humberside area. Third was Pounds 150m from the management-employee
buy-out team, and fourth Ocean Group, the distribution company, which is
believed to have bid about the same.
The fact that the buy-out team was outbid did not eliminate it from the
contest. The trust had agreed with the government that price would be only
one of three main criteria, the others being employee participation and
benefits to the local economy.
The trust provoked furious protests from the buy-out team, other contenders
and local MPs by awarding victory neither to the highest bidder nor to the
buy-out team but to Teesside Holdings. Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the transport
secretary, has said he is 'minded' to approve that decision.
In a 13-page memorandum to the prime minister, Mr Stuart Bell, Labour MP for
Middlesbrough, claims that: Teesside Holdings' bid said that, if it won,
room would be made on the company's board for one of the trust's
non-executives, thus presenting the judges with an unacceptable conflict of
interest.
Two of Teesside's directors had previously been directors of port companies
that were put into liquidation in 1989, tion to meet redundancy payments of
Pounds 6.6m.
The Teesside bid provided for employee ownership of only 5 per cent of the
shares, so failing to meet one of the criteria: the desirability of seeing
the whole, or a substantial part, of the equity taken by managers and
employees.
Teesside was given the opportunity to bring in other investors and increase
its bid twice during the contest.
The buy-out team says that, if it had known employee participation would
count for so little, it could have brought in other equity investors and
pipped the Teesside bid.
Price Waterhouse, the accountancy firm advising the Department of Transport,
says the buy-out team is being a poor loser. It simply misjudged the value
of the preference the trust and the government would put on a
management-employee buy-out.
That is not the end of the affair. The Tees &amp; Hartlepool buy-out team says
it will seek a judicial review of the trust's decision if Mr Rifkind
confirms it this week. Worse, the managements of several other trust ports -
Clyde, Medway, Tilbury and Forth - have privatisation plans in train, each
raising the possibility of a fresh political row.
To try to limit the potential for embarrassment, the Transport Department
has imposed an information blackout on future competitive tenders so that
bids will remain secret. It is also allowing Forth to avoid the tendering
process by floating itself on the stock market, so undermining its own
value-for-money principle.
Whether those measures will be enough to forestall further rows is
uncertain. MPs seem unlikely to be impressed by them and disappointed
bidders in competitive tenders may still break their vows of silence. Unless
Mr Rifkind has a last-minute change of heart over Tees &amp; Hartlepool, the
controversy over that sale seems destined to haunt him until the general
election.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
