<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Personal-distress awards sharply up in
bias cases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AWARDS for injury to feelings in discrimination cases have more than doubled
since 1988, according to a study by Industrial Relations Services (IRS), the
independent research organisation.
However, IRS said the increase masked wide variations within the sex and
race jurisdictions, with tribunals much more likely to award aggravated
damages in race cases than in sex cases.
The report showed that few industrial tribunals made exemplary awards that
were punitive rather than compensatory and so aimed to deter employers from
similar action.
Injury-to-feelings awards began to rise in early 1988 after the Court of
Appeals set new parameters for the level of such awards in discrimination
cases. It said awards should not be nominal and may include aggravated
damages, putting Pounds 3,000 at the top end of the range.
Equal Opportunities Review, Number 41. From IRS, 18-20 Highbury Place,
London N5 1QP. By subscription.
