<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): 'Going rate' still applies in pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 'GOING RATE' is alive and well in British pay setting, according to Mr
Fred Bayliss, a former senior official in the Department of Employment.
He said in a paper prepared for the lobby group Campaign for Work that in
spite of continuing decentralisation of collective bargaining, control over
pay was now in fewer, not more, hands than 15 years ago.
Mr Bayliss took issue with the group's claim that to achieve a better
trade-off between pay and employment, the bargaining process had to be
synchronised around a couple of months every year.
He said that already more than half of all employees in the private sector
had their pay settlements between January and April and argued that
co-ordination of the level of annual pay rise was the key rather than
synchronisation.
Mr Bayliss concluded, after examining pay determination in retailing, banks,
building societies, the car industry and chemicals, that many of the
preconditions for better co-ordination already existed.
He found that companies had their place in a pay pecking order, that there
was a great deal of informal consultation between companies and a strong
desire not to be knowingly adrift of others on pay.
There continued to be acknowledged pay 'leaders'. Mr Bayliss said in
retailing Sainsbury, Marks and Spencer and Tesco were the 'heavyweights'. In
banks, Barclays now settled first but NatWest still carried 'about as much
weight'. Among building societies, Abbey National was the leader and in
chemicals everyone watched ICI. In vehicle manufacture, Ford 'is well
established'.
Mr Bayliss accepted that for co-ordinated pay to be successful, key
companies would have to subordinate 'their separate company and sector
goals'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
