<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / Tempered optimism in west Midlands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES in the west Midlands, one of the country's main business regions,
report a slight increase in confidence, although the outlook remains
difficult, according to a study published today.
The West Midlands Regional Group of Chambers of Commerce says 48 per cent of
companies in the area think sales will rise over the next year, compared
with a figure of 43 per cent in September 1991.
However, Mr Howard Davis, chairman of the regional group, said that growth
prospects remained poor. He wanted the government to reintroduce 100 per
cent capital allowances to boost manufacturing investment and output. The
allowances, which would enable companies to offset capital spending against
profits, would be a sign that ministers were considering the plight of
industry.
He added that it would also tackle the large fall in manufacturing
investment over the past year 'which must affect the ability of industry to
compete as we pull out of recession'.
In the survey of nearly 700 manufacturing and service companies the
proportion expecting a rise in profits increased to 37 per cent, from 34 per
cent in September.
Just over a quarter of companies in the study, which was conducted in
December, have fuller export order books compared with three months
previously. The comparable figure in September was 21 per cent.
According to the survey 15 per cent of companies in the region are working
at full capacity and 11 per cent at below 60 per cent capacity.
Nearly a fifth of businesses say they are finding cashflow easier than three
months ago, while 29 per cent say it is worse. The comparable figures for
September were 16 per cent and 32 per cent.
Consumer confidence is low and will recover only slowly this year, according
to Infolink, which monitors demand for credit. In November 1991, demand for
credit to buy retail goods was up just 9.2 per cent compared with the same
month in 1990, which Infolink says is extremely low for the pre-Christmas
period.
</TEXT>
