FT  13 JAN 92 / Delay over BR sell-off proposals denied
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS yesterday insisted that a white paper paving the way for the
privatisation of British Rail would appear before the general election in
spite of a Cabinet split over the form it should take, Richard Tomkins
writes.
Weekend reports speculated that the difficulties of resolving ministerial
differences might cause an indefinite postponement of the white paper in
favour of a manifesto pledge.
Even so, the Department of Transport was yesterday sticking to its promise
that a white paper would appear by the end of January or, at the latest, in
early February.
Ministers are united in their belief that British Rail should not enter the
private sector in its present form as a large, unwieldy monopoly but are at
odds over how it should be broken up.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the transport secretary, believes it should be split
along the lines of its existing business sectors while Mr John Major, the
prime minister, is said to favour a regional division. Other ministers
believe the ownership of the tracks and trains should be separated.
Sir Bob Reid, Page 28
