<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / Ashdown hardens coalition terms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PADDY Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, yesterday toughened the
conditions for his support in a hung parliament to include agreement on a
four-year government programme and no income tax cuts.
Mr Ashdown said opinion polls showed a balanced parliament after the general
election was 'likely'. Liberal Democrats would seek a 'powerful role' in
creating a stable government that implemented as many of his party's
policies as possible, most crucially on electoral reform.
He stood by the pledge to raise income tax if necessary to fund education
reform and to increase taxes on scarce resources, including petrol.
Asked if he could support a Tory government committed to cutting income tax
to 20 per cent, he said: 'I wouldn't be prepared to do anything that would
be bankrupting for the country or further debilitate our public services.'
Senior Liberal Democrat MPs and officials decided at a final election
strategy meeting that the party would try to ensure that constitutional
reform was not pushed off the political agenda by Labour or the Tories.
They would resist making personal attacks on Mr John Major or Mr Neil
Kinnock, Labour leader - even if that meant the party was denied media
attention during the election campaign.
Liberal Democrat strategists argue that opinion polls are understating
support for the party. Private polling, they say, shows that as many as 49
per cent of voters would support them if they thought the party had a chance
of winning power.
Mr Ashdown appealed to such voters, considered to be latent supporters, in
his interview on BBC Radio yesterday. He said that the more people voted for
the Liberal Democrats, the more their policies would be implemented.
He disliked Labour and the Tories equally, he said, but in the event of a
hung parliament the possible coalition partner for the Liberal Democrats
would probably have been determined by the election result.
'What our aim is, is stable government and successful government for Britain
over four years,' Mr Ashdown said.
'That means a government whose cornerstone is an effective majority in the
House of Commons. It means a government whose reform programme includes
proportional representation . . . and it means a successful programme for
the government to start to implement.'
He said proportional representation was the 'essential prerequisite' for
stable government. Liberal Democrats would insist on the necessary
legislation being implemented within the lifetime of a parliament.
</TEXT>
