<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / Poor hopes for sales of companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MARKET for selling unquoted businesses was depressed last year and there
is little prospect of an upturn this year, according to Ernst &amp; Young, the
accountants.
Prices were lower in 1991 than in previous years and were also low relative
to the sums paid for similar quoted companies. Many of the sales that were
made resulted from companies' going into receivership or administration or
were distress sales intended to raise desperately needed cash.
In the UK, companies were already over-borrowed and would need to devote
their resources to rebuilding finances rather than making acquisitions.
Companies in continental Europe that paid what seemed generous prices for UK
companies over the past two years were less keen to make foreign
acquisitions now that their own economies were moving into recession.
Nevertheless, for buyers who were confident of the future, this year should
be good for making purchases, Ernst &amp; Young said. The economic cycle was at
or near its trough, while vendors should be more realistic in their price
expectations.
</TEXT>
