<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / Algerian poll cancelled after Chadli quits office: Armoured
vehicles in capital - Islamic party denied victory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALGERIA'S transition to democracy received a severe setback last night when
the country's leaders cancelled general elections which looked certain to
hand power to Moslem fundamentalists.
As tanks guarded government buildings in the capital, Algiers, the High
Security Council said the elections could not be continued 'until necessary
conditions were achieved for the normal functioning of institutions'.
Effective power following the resignation on Saturday of President Chadli
Bendjedid now rests with the High Security Council. This includes prime
minister Sid Ahmed Ghozali, senior military commanders and the interim
president, Mr Abdelmalek Benhabyles, who is also chairman of the
Constitutional Council, the top legal body.
The High Security Council said it had taken charge provisionally of public
order and security. Its intervention prompted a strong reaction from Hocine
Ait-Ahmed, leader of the Front des Forces Socialistes, the main lay
opposition, who said on French radio that the country was witnessing a coup
'if not in form, then certainly in fact'.
A second round of the elections, Algeria's first multi-party contest, was
due to take place on Thursday. In the first round on December 26, the
Islamic Salvation Front (FIS), which aims to turn Algeria into North
Africa's first Islamic state, took a landslide lead with 188 seats in the
430-seat National Assembly.
Mr Chadli's resignation after some 13 years in power came after pressure
from military officers and many other groups representing professional
bodies, trade unions and women.
The FIS called the resignation a 'piece of theatre aimed at suppressing the
people and cancelling the results'. FIS militants gathered outside the
party's headquarters in Algiers, awaiting directions from their leaders. The
capital and other main cities were subdued, however.
Tanks were stationed in front of the prime minister's office, the Ministry
of the Interior and the state television building. But the presence of the
army remained very discreet, with troops confined essentially to the
barracks on the city's outskirts.
Before the High Security Council's intervention last night, the National
Liberation Front, which held a monopoly on power in Algeria until 1988 and
was thrashed in December's polls, reiterated its commitment to the
elections.
The Defence Ministry said that the army 'reaffirms its loyalty to the
constitution and its confidence in the existing constitutional
institutions'. Under the constitution, Mr Benhabyles has 45 days as interim
head of state to organise a presidential election.
France, the former colonial power, has plans to accommodate refugees who
would flee an Islamic state in Algeria if one came into being, according to
Mr Philippe Marchand, the Paris interior minister.
Meanwhile, Britain was among countries which advised their nationals to
avoid travelling to Algeria because of the crisis.
The Foreign Office advised the 200 Britons living in the country to stay in
touch with the embassy and 'to take sensible precautions . . . and avoid
potential troublespots'.
Establishment's anxieties spell the end for Chadli Page 5
Editorial comment Page 12
</TEXT>
