FT  13 JAN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you prefer factual programmes tonight's the night. Horizon (8.10 BBC2)
investigates the increasing use of natural predators and parasites in pest
control in preference to the chemicals which have been so heavily used in
the past 50 years. Not only do pests develop resistence to chemical
controls, but the poisons often reach human consumers. However, as
Australia's plague of cane toads demonstrates, not all man's attempts at
exploiting predators are successful.
In Britain feral mink, the subject of Wildlife On One (8.30), are loathed
almost as much as cane toads in Australia. Originally imported from the US
to be farmed for the fur trade, they have returned to the wild, colonised
most of the country, and are now reputed to be our most ferocious mammal. In
a postponed programme World In Action (8.30 ITV) reports how the Japanese
are logging all the hardwood out of Borneo while protecting their own
timber. Channel 4 begins what is claimed to be the definitive series on The
Falklands War in four parts (9.00). Panorama (9.30 BBC1) looks at death in
the workplace in Britain and the way that managements almost invariably
emerge unscathed.
</TEXT>
