<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / MPs voice fears over investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SUBSTANTIAL percentage of backbench MPs believes that planned levels of
infrastructural investment are inadequate, according to a poll of 100 MPs
carried out for the Federation of Civil Engineering Contractors.
Asked about investment plans over the next three years, 58 MPs thought
spending plans for railway infrastructure were inadequate, and 44 believed
the same for road spending plans.
Sewage treatment and water supply investment plans were classed as
inadequate by 47 and 39 MPs respectively, while 35 thought energy
infrastructure plans were insufficient for Britain's needs.
The survey was carried out by Access Opinions in November and December, and
based on the standing of the parties in the present House of Commons - 58
Conservatives, 35 Labour and seven others.
Spending plans in all categories were regarded with less concern on the
government's backbenches than on the opposition's. Even so, one-third of the
Tory MPs polled thought planned investment in railway infrastructure was
inadequate for Britain's needs.
</TEXT>
