<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (22): Takeover battle a rousing but
untypical climax - Mergers and acquisitions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN OLD-FASHIONED Anglo-Saxon takeover battle brought the 1991 European
mergers and acquisitions scene to a rousing but untypical climax.
BTR, the UK industrial conglomerate ranked 22nd in the FT500, won its Pounds
1.55bn hostile bid for Hawker Siddeley, one of the most famous names in
British engineering, which was ranked 186.
However, hopes that BTR's return to the takeover trail marked a resurgence
in UK takeover activity proved unfounded - as did speculation that Hanson's
taking of a 2.8 per stake in Imperial Chemical Industries would lead to a
bid for the giant.
The hostility with which Lord Hanson's stake-building was greeted by
politicians demonstrated just how much the commercial climate has changed in
the UK since the deal-driven 1980s.
The combination of recession, shortage of bank finance and uncertainty
caused by the Gulf war all helped reduce cross-border M&amp;A activity to its
lowest level since the crash of October 1987. According to the accounting
group KPMG, the value of cross-border deals in the first nine months of the
year fell by 60 per cent, to Dollars 34.8bn
Takeover activity in Europe fell less steeply, mainly because of the
continuing drive by companies to consolidate and strengthen their position
ahead of the unified market.
Financial services saw some of the greatest concentration. In the
Netherlands, the merger of the country's two largest banks,
Amsterdam-Rotterdam Bank (Amro Bank) and Algemene Bank Nederland (ABN Bank),
formed ABN-Amro Holding, ranked 84 in the FT500.
Then Nationale-Nederlande, the leading Dutch insurer, merged with NMB
Postbank, the country's third-biggest bank, to create the Internationale
Nederlanden group, which is ranked 72nd.
One company's focusing often gave a rival an opportunity to buy market
share. AEG, part of the Daimler-Benz industrial group of Germany, sold its
cable business to Alcatel Alsthom of France as part of its strategy of
concentrating on its main activities.
AEG Kabel said the business would have required too much investment to make
it a big enough competitor on the European market. The purchase lifted
Alcatel Cable's share of the German market from 10 to nearly 25 per cent.
This process of concentration often posed regulatory questions. The EC's
merger task force, which began routine investigations in January 1991
approved the SKr16.25bn (Dollars 2.8bn) bid for Alfa-Laval, the Swedish
dairy and food processing equipment company, by Tetra Pak, the Swiss
packaging group. Both companies had promised not to make sales of packaging
machinery dependent on orders for processing machinery. They also undertook
to make equipment compatible with competitors' products.
Sir Leon Brittan, competition commissioner, allowed Fiat to take a
controlling interest in Alcatel Alsthom's battery operations, though on
condition the Italian group sold most of its stake in a large French battery
maker.
However, Brussels banned a proposed takeover of de Havilland, the ailing
Canadian offshoot of Boeing, by Aerospatiale of France and Alenia of Italy.
The EC said the proposed takeover would have created 'a powerful and
unassailable dominant position in the world market for turbo-prop (commuter)
aircraft'.
Occasionally changes in government regulation speeded the restructuring of
markets. Allied-Lyons, the UK drinks, food and retailing group, and
Carlsberg, the Danish brewer, plan to merge their UK brewing interests in a
Pounds 510m joint venture. The deal marks a further consolidation of the
British brewing industry after the UK's Monopolies and Mergers Commission's
unsuccessful attempt to loosen the national brewers' grip on pub retailing.
According to KPMG, French companies overtook UK groups as the biggest
acquirers abroad during the first nine months of 1991, although French M&amp;A
activity was also down on the previous year.
Much of the French activity was in the US, with Schneider, the electrical
equipment company, taking over Square D, the electrical distribution group
for Dollars 2.23bn. Axa, France's second largest insurer, took a FFr5.8bn
(Dollars 1.07bn) stake in the Equitable Life Assurance Society, and Alcatel
Alsthom, the engineering and telecommunications group, paid FFr3.8bn for the
transmission equipment division of Rockwell.
On the domestic front, however, France is debating how its two-year-old
takeover legislation reforms are working. Under the rules, a shareholder who
raises his stake in a firm's capital or voting rights to above one half must
bid for full control.
But a shareholder who takes his stake above one third can get away with
raising that to a minimum of just two thirds. In those cases, critics say,
minorities left with the remaining one-third are discriminated against, as
there is no guarantee they will be able to sell their stock at the bid
price.
Mr Pierre Beregovoy, France's finance minister, said recently he did not
rule out the need to modify the regulations, but felt there was no consensus
for change.
In Germany, the collapse of talks between Continental, the tyre-making
group, and Pirelli of Italy rekindled fears of a 'Fortress Germany', from
which foreign bidders would be excluded by a combination of banks,
cross-holdings of shares and voting right limits.
Mr Hubertus von Grunberg, chief executive of Continental, admitted the
collapse of the talks could have a negative effect on the German M&amp;A scene:
'It wasn't our intention, but the whole thing could be rather discouraging
for others contemplating mergers or acquisitions.'
The UK continues to be worried by a draft EC directive which would harmonise
takeover practices throughout the Community. The British would, of course,
welcome a more liberal regime, encouraging more aggressive takeovers.
However, the UK's Takeover Panel is concerned that any EC directive would
threaten the self-regulatory and non-statutory basis of the UK approach,
which has the advantage of keeping companies out of the courts.
