<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (20): Recession the watchword -
Country Analysis, The UK / Some companies slipped deeply into the doldrums
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECESSION has been the watchword for UK companies this year as the economy
continued to contract in the first six months. There was a slight rally in
the third quarter, thanks to the oil sector.
Yet, because the London stock market looks several months ahead - in this
case to recovery - the value of UK stocks in the survey tended to rise from
their cheap levels on the way into recession, compounded by the Gulf crisis.
Taking the snapshot dates for the FT500, the FT-SE 100 index rose by more
than 10 per cent between the end of June last year and September 30 this
year, although it then fell back.
The rise helps to explain the additional 16 UK companies in the top 500,
taking the total to 181 (not counting double listings such as the survey
leader Royal Dutch/Shell). This is almost three times the representation of
France and Germany, where far fewer companies are quoted and the
takeover-based trends towards multi-nationalism and concentrations within
industries are far weaker.
Yet whatever the hopes for recovery in some sectors, others slipped deeply
into the doldrums and this is reflected in their declining rankings. The
testing conditions also vindicated a few theories about recession-resilience
and highlighted the quality of some individual managements.
Perhaps the worst affected family of sectors was property and building, with
repercussions to insurance through the underwriting losses on mortgage
indemnities.
Even Land Securities, the largest and most robust property company in the UK
and one of the very few to manage an interim profits increase, drifted down
from 94 to 101.
Ladbroke, the hotel and leisure group, and Peninsular and Oriental Steam
Navigation, which is also involved in construction, were vulnerable not only
through their property divisions, but through stretched balance sheets. Both
had rights issues - another theme for the year.
The previous annual record of nearly Pounds 7bn raised in 1987 was surpassed
within the first eight months of this year. Companies took advantage of
rising share prices to repair balance sheets or to strengthen their hands in
bids for struggling targets.
By December, about Pounds 9bn had been raised. But not all the calls were
well received, particularly as heavily tapped institutions became more
selective. Most ignominious was the less than 5 per cent take-up of British
Aerospace's Pounds 432m issue.
Construction companies were fairly well represented in the rights issue
roll, but the leading house builders were not among them after a bad year on
all fronts - including their share prices.
Tarmac and Wimpey, duly fell down the rankings as private housing starts
sank to about 130,000 this year, about 90,000 - or 40 per cent - fewer than
in 1988.
Meanwhile, the insurers of over-mortgaged individuals lost a lot of money -
Royal Insurance announced underwriting losses of Pounds 173m for the nine
months to the end of September.
While it was clearly easy for companies and individuals to defer buying
property, some aspects of life went on regardless. Those stocks dealing in
such non-discretionary items as food and health duly proved their
resilience.
Glaxo, the drugs company catering for ailments as prevalent as ulcers,
asthma and migraine, rose from 10th to third and Wellcome also progressed
impressively from 64 to 27.
Drugs companies have proved to be good examples of several positive factors
valued by equity analysts: they operate in growth markets and have extensive
international earnings. The increasing sophistication of treatments
justifies higher prices and the specialist products are, by definition,
aimed at niche markets.
This provides all the ingredients for that lucrative cliche 'high added
value' and it can be seen in Wellcome's pre-tax profit margin of nearly 25
per cent in its latest set of interim results.
Food has also provided a haven for many an investor this year. J Sainsbury
and Tesco, two aggressive expanders of their supermarket chains, have both
jumped more than 20 places to 33 and 47 respectively. But they still lag
behind Marks and Spencer, which has applied both the value for money and
added value formulae to a wider range of goods.
Other retailers dealing in the modern versions of staple goods, such as
toothpaste and toilet rolls, follow a similar pattern, with Boots as an
obvious example.
Food manufacturers also did well - Northern Foods, for instance - and the
makers of alcoholic drinks were largely unaffected by the conditions, with
Guinness as a prime example. Allied-Lyons, spread across drinks, food and
retailing, benefited accordingly. There was even a positive spin-off for
companies tranporting the necessities, such as NFC.
It could almost be called the year for essentials when the rises of
companies associated with heat, light and water are added in, following in
the wake of longer-established brethren in the oil sector.
British Gas rose from 14th to 7th, close to British Petroleum in ranking but
still less than two thirds of its value. The water companies, new to the
index last year, rose strongly headed by Thames at 197 (254). Southern and
Welsh were new entrants.
But the most prominent performance was the entry of a dozen electricity
concerns, following this year's privatisations. National Power came in at
87, the second highest new entry behind Vodafone at 65, in the growth market
of mobile communications, which demerged fully from Racal Electronics in
August.
Vodafone's parent, on the other hand, was the biggest faller, from 96 to
351. Its vulnerability sparked a bid from Williams Holdings, a rapid riser
through its exploitation of acquisition opportunities.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-15081</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAMBUAARFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (18): Picture is almost universally
negative - Engineering / The financial effect of the downturn is hard to
gauge, as so much of the industry remains in private hands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT HAS been a tough year for the European engineering industry, with a deep
recession that began in the UK in the middle of last year spreading
gradually to the continent, reaching Germany - albeit with reduced vigour -
by spring this year.
The downturn in western European demand has combined with a much-needed
sense of realism about the long-term needs for capital goods in reunified
Germany and eastern Europe, choking off some of the initial euphoria.
The financial effect of the downturn on European engineering is hard to
gauge, as so much of the industry remains in private hands. Inevitably,
therefore, important but predominantly private industries such as machine
tools, which by this summer were having a hard time virtually everywhere in
Europe, and construction equipment, which is being buoyed by German demand,
have little impact on the FT500.
Nevertheless, the big publicly-quoted steel, metals and engineering
companies that are in the index do give a reasonable indication of investor
perceptions across a broad cross-section of industry, and the picture
presented is almost universally negative.
Virtually all such companies saw their position in the rankings slip this
year. At the top end Siemens, with its significant transportation and power
generating equipment interests, slipped from seventh to ninth, while ABB
Asea Brown Boveri, the Swiss-Swedish engineering group, dropped from 16th to
31st.
Further down the list, it is the same story, with solid engineering names
such as Linde, Sandvik, Siebe, TI Group and Sulzer all registering declines
of varying intensity. One of the most famous names in UK engineering,
Vickers, only just managed to stay in the rankings, dropping from 432nd to
499th, having warned towards the end of September that its final dividend
depended on an improvement in outlook for Rolls-Royce motor cars.
There are some notable departures, most of which were pushed out by
non-engineering companies rather than by the more honourable exit route via
acquisition. The biggest takeover in the engineering industry this year saw
the absorption of Alfa-Laval, the Swedish food, dairy and industrial
equipment producer ranked 185th last year, by Tetra Pak, the privately-owned
packaging company.
Among eight further names to have dropped out are Klockner-Humboldt-Deutz
(414th last year), which is expecting flat profits this year, Dowty (459th),
the UK aerospace and electronics group caught up in the defence downturn,
and FAG Kugelfischer (460th), the German bearings group.
The one entrant to the rankings, at 220th, is Pechiney International, a
recently-established, separately-quoted subsidiary of Pechiney, the French
state-controlled aluminium and packaging group which retains a 75 per cent
stake. It comprises most of the group's foreign activities, including
American National Can.
It should be pointed out that there are structural as well as cyclical
reasons for the general decline, along with the shortage of new entrants. In
the engineering industry, this has not been a big year for the kind of
mega-merger activity which would have an impact on the FT500.
The restructuring in mechanical and electrical engineering at the end of the
1980s was not only prompted by overcapacity in many important sectors, but
by the closely-linked desire by companies to get mergers out of the way, and
new structures in place, well ahead of the 1992 European Community Single
Market reforms.
There is, however, a reasonable amount of takeover and joint venture
activity of the kind that by definition impinges on the FT500 rankings
slowly or indirectly. However, the Gulf war caused as much uncertainty over
long-term planning in the engineering industry as elsewhere.
It is also important to note that, although the declines in rankings are
pervasive, business conditions and prospects vary widely. The gloomiest
sector is almost certainly the steel industry, where the three big
publicly-quoted producers, Thyssen, British Steel and Hoesch, all suffered
sharp falls in their European 500 positions.
In spite of a decade of restructuring, a majority of European steel plants
are either making losses or just breaking even, according to a confidential
survey prepared for the European Commission this summer. Prices have been
cut as national markets such as the UK, hitherto the preserve of British
Steel, have become more open to foreign competition.
As it happens, this survey of the industry's costs put both British Steel
and Thyssen in a low-cost group, with Hoesch and its recent suitor Fried.
Krupp in the medium-cost group. A stock market quotation has clearly spurred
British Steel to increase efficiency, but its financial health, and perhaps
its European 500 ranking - down from 84th to 105th this year - might improve
with further thorough restructuring among its German rivals.
Indeed next year's rankings could reflect that, if Krupp completes a planned
merger with Hoesch which would create a new power in the steel and
engineering industries. Krupp is not publicly-quoted.
Elsewhere, the slip down the rankings by leading engineering groups has
almost certainly been checked by the cushioning effect of their varying
internal business cycles. ABB, for example, has been stressing all year the
disparity between such 'standard products' as electrical installation
equipment for housing, which have been hit by recession, and infrastructural
businesses such as power generating equipment which is much more influenced
by longer-term buying trends.
As for machinery companies, the outlook may not look too bright, but one of
the more thoughtful observers of the European capital goods scene, Mr Edward
Hadas of Morgan Stanley, believes the future looks much better for selected
companies if they can benefit from a virtuous circle of low production costs
accompanied by higher product prices, while superior quality leads to
increased market share.
'After many years of struggle, an increasing number of companies in Europe
find themselves going round the first turns of this happy curve,' he says.
Furthermore, he says, the impact of eastern Europe on the machinery industry
should be more significant than for the western European economy as a whole,
and come quite soon.
Among quoted companies, he believes the best beneficiary of the forthcoming
upturn will be Mannesmann - down in this year's rankings from 68th to 91st -
partly because of leadership in several key machinery sectors.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXIV
</PAGE>
