<PROFILE>_AN-CAMBUAAKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (11): Mergers transform financial
sector - The Netherlands - Trend towards concentration gathers pace among
insurers and banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE two biggest Dutch companies in this year's FT500 (excluding the
Anglo-Dutch giants Royal Dutch/Shell and Unilever) are newcomers to the
annual rankings, yet they are also very much part of the Netherlands
corporate establishment.
This seeming paradox is easily explained: both entries '
Internationale-Nederlanden Groep (ING), the financial services company, and
ABN Amro, the country's biggest bank ' are the product of two recent, huge
corporate mergers between four of the Netherlands's best-known institutions,
underscoring the rapid and radical transformation of the Dutch financial
sector.
The birth of ING is a compelling illustration of just how quickly the trend
towards concentration has gathered pace among Dutch insurers and banks over
the past two years. NMB Postbank, the country's third-largest bank which
merged with the Netherlands's biggest insurer Nationale-Nederlanden to
produce the new combine in early 1991, was itself the product of a merger
just a year earlier.
The emergence of ING also testifies to another new trend in the Dutch world
of finance ' the development of the 'All-Finanz' concept, in which insurers
and banks combine to create a financial services 'supermarket' in the hope
of attracting the consumer to a wide range of financial products.
Of the Netherlands's three leading insurers, only Aegon has yet to forge a
link with a bank. Amev, the third-largest Dutch insurer, earlier took over
VSB, the Netherlands's biggest savings bank group, before merging with the
Belgian insurer AG to form Fortis, which enters the FT500 for the first time
this year in 167th place.
Apart from the creation of Fortis, the recent series of big mergers has not
involved cross-border link-ups, belying earlier expectations in the
Netherlands that there would be a wave of European corporate marriages in
the run-up to 1992 and the EC single market. A clear preference for local
partners has emerged, at least in the short term, though the long-term
rationale behind most of the financial-sector mergers has been a desire to
create a springboard for European acquisitions.
This tendency to seek out local rather than foreign merger partners is best
illustrated by the merger between ABN Bank and Amro Bank, now called ABN
Amro. Before entering negotiations with ABN, Amro had been involved in an
ill-fated attempt to arrive at a full link-up with its Belgian counterpart
Generale de Banque. This proposed bi-national merger foundered on cultural
differences and the lack of common European corporate legislation.
Still, the Netherlands may yet see a big European link-up, one which would
bring substantial changes to future FT500s. In late 1991, KLM, the
Netherlands's flag carrier, confirmed that it was engaged in talks on a
far-reaching partnership with British Airways. These talks, if successful,
could result in the creation of a formidable European mega-carrier.
An outright merger is less likely than a construction which would enable
both KLM and BA to retain their separate legal identities and stock market
listings. If this indeed proves to be the case, KLM and BA will be following
in the successful Anglo-Dutch traditions of Royal Dutch/Shell and Unilever,
ranked first and fifth respectively in the FT500.
The Dutch companies in this year's rankings provide a good mini-portrait of
the Netherlands's corporate sector. The Netherlands, which was late to
industrialise in the 19th century, is strongest in trade, services and
agriculture-related activities. Of the 16 purely Dutch companies included
this year, the only industrial concerns are Philips, the electronics
company; Akzo and DSM, the chemicals companies; KNP, the paper group; and
Buhrmann-Tetterode, the packaging and graphic equipment company.
In addition to these companies, the financial sector groups and KLM, other
entries include two Dutch publishing houses with strong international
connections, Elsevier and Wolters Kluwer, as well as Heineken, the brewery
group, and Ahold, a food retailer which generates half of its sales along
the US east coast. A new entry at number 494, the food company Nutricia, is
due in part to the good performance of the food sector on the Amsterdam
stock exchange in 1991.
The inclusion of two property investment groups, Rodamco and Wereldhave,
testifies to the Netherlands's long-standing involvement in overseas
investment, an area forced upon it by the severely limited size of its home
market. Rodamco, part of the Rotterdam-based Robeco investment group, saw
its ranking plummet to 132nd place from 77th in 1990.
The sharp drop is a consequence of Rodamco's sudden decision in September
1990 to suspend its previous policy of making daily purchases and disposals
of its own shares on the Amsterdam bourse to ensure that its share price was
always equivalent to the prevailing net asset value of its property
portfolio. By retracting this guarantee, Rodamco effectively transformed
itself from an open-end into a close-end fund. Since then, its shares have
traded at a discount of 20 per cent or more to net asset value, accounting
for the steep decline in Rodamco's market capitalisation between mid-1990
and mid-1991.
Although the FT500 offers a capsule view of the corporate sector, its
measurement of companies by market capitalisation means it does not include
family-owned concerns or those organised along co-operative lines, such as
Rabobank, the Netherlands's second-largest bank. Like its bourse-listed
rivals, Rabobank was also converted to the concept of 'All-Finanz' when it
took full control over Interpolis, a co-operatively-owned insurer, in 1990.
Because of the strength of Dutch agriculture in particular, co-operatives '
ranging from dairy organisations to flower and plant auctions ' play a large
role in the economy. Their structure, however, makes it difficult for
co-operatives to issue shares that can be traded on the stock market.
Later this year, OPG, a pharmaceuticals purchasing co-operative owned by
more than 2,000 Dutch chemists, hopes to become the first Dutch co-operative
to get around this problem and launch a share flotation in Amsterdam. OPG's
solution is to establish a trust company and make it an extraordinary member
of the co-operative. The trust company, in turn, acquires participation
certificates in the co-operative (including a right to future dividends) and
uses these as a basis for issuing shares to the public.
In the absence of any substantial state holdings in industry left to
privatise, this formula, if successful, could potentially become one of the
Amsterdam bourse's most important vehicles for attracting new listings in
the 1990s.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-15089</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAMBUAAJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (9): Denmark bucks the downward
trend - Nordic Region - The majority of companies experienced a substantial
fall in market capitalisation, particularly those in Finland and Sweden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE majority of Nordic-based companies listed in the FT500 experienced a
substantial fall in market capitalisation, particularly those in Finland and
Sweden. Only Denmark bucked the overall downward trend with a relatively
impressive performance, reflecting the country's economic achievements.
Most of Sweden's leading companies experienced severe troubles during 1991
with declining production, investments and profitability. Eight disappeared
from the FT500 - NCC, the construction group, Nobel Industries, the office
equipment company Esselte, Gota bank group, the cement company Euroc, and
Cardo, the investment company.
Saab-Scania, the motor and aerospace company, left the bourse after all its
shares were acquired by the Wallenberg family-dominated investment
companies. In November, it was announced that Investor and Providentia were
to be merged into one company early this year. The other large company to
leave the bourse was the dairy company Alfa Laval as a result of its
acquisition by the Swiss-based packaging firm Tetra Pak.
Four new corporate entrants appeared from Sweden - Gambro, the
pharmaceuticals company, the newly-floated Wallenberg industrial group
Incentive, and the Wallenberg investment companies Investor and Providentia.
It is indicative of Sweden's dismal industrial scene that only three of the
29 Swedish companies in the FT500 improved their relative positions during
the year.
The successful pharmaceuticals company Astra climbed from 48th to 37th to
become the highest placed Swedish company. In the first nine months of the
year its profits rose by 40 per cent to SKr2.58bn (Dollars 447m), due mainly
to the continuing rise in demand for its anti-ulcer drug Losec.
The food and pharmaceuticals conglomerate Procordia - owned jointly by Volvo
and the Swedish state - rose nine places from 58th to 49th. Its earnings
rose by 23 per cent in the first nine months of 1991 to Skr3.08bn.
The only other Swedish company to climb up the table was the insurance
conglomerate Trygg-Hansa SPP, which was formed after a merger earlier in the
year. The new conglomerate rose impressively to 321st from its 1990 ranking
of 417th when Trygg-Hansa first entered the table after its flotation on the
Stockholm bourse in December 1989. Its profits for the first eight months of
the year totalled Skr1.5bn, a quadrupling of its figure in 1990, mainly
because of the improved performance of its investment portfolio.
By contrast, a number of Swedish companies suffered sharp falls in relative
market capitalisation during 1991. The troubled state-controlled Nordbanken
dropped the largest number of places from 200th to 476th. This reflected the
market's response to its mounting credit losses that look likely to total
nearly SKr10bn for the year, ensuring the bank has a group deficit of around
SKr4.6bn.
The largest construction company in the Nordic region, Skanska, also dropped
back to 169th position from 93rd in 1990. Its profits declined to SKr1.19bn
from SKr1.71bn for the first eight months of the year, reflecting the fall
in real estate prices and slump in the building trade.
The mineral and industrial conglomerate Trelleborg - one of Sweden's
corporate success stories of the 1980s - declined as well, dropping to 422nd
from 312th.
The corporate picture was even more dismal in Finland during 1991. This
reflected the country's worst recession since 1917 with the virtual collapse
of its once-important Soviet trade, a cyclical trough in the paper and pulp
industry, soaring bank credit losses, and a slump in engineering production
and investment. The combination of these adverse economic factors forced the
Helsinki bourse into a sharp decline.
Fewer than half the Finnish-based companies listed in the 1990 FT500
re-appear this time. Out go the state-controlled forestry group Enso
Gutzeit, the shipbuilding company Wartsila, the industrial group Rauma
Repola, Sampo and Pohjola insurance companies, the wholesalers Kesko Oy and
Partek, the building materials group.
As a result only five corporate entrants remain from Finland - the forestry
groups Repola (after the merger of United Paper Mills with Rauma-Repola) and
Kymmene; the industrial conglomerate Nokia; and two banks, Union Bank and
Kansallis-Osake-Pankki (KOP). Of those only Repola recorded an improved its
position - climbing from 485th to 325th.
By contrast, Denmark enjoyed a highly satisfactory corporate year. The
country may have an industrial structure where small and medium-sized
companies predominate but as a favourable sign of its economic success story
this year the country can boast 12 companies in the FT500, three more than
in 1990 with not one falling out of the table.
The most impressive arrival was A P Moeller, the merchant shipping company
in the form of its strange, divided structure which consists of twin parent
companies D/S af 1912 and A/S D/S Svendborg. As newcomers to the table they
appear at 141st and 142nd positions respectively. Berendsen (Sophus), a
diverse industrial company that is the parent of Rentokil was also a
newcomer to the FT500 in 1991.
Novo Nordisk, Denmark's leading pharmaceutical company which is the world's
leading producer of industrial enzymes, also performed well in 1991,
climbing 92 places to 208th position from 317th. As a producer of insulin
and diabetic care products, it now has 40 per cent of the world market in
those products. In the first nine months of 1991 the company's profits
climbed by 22 per cent to a healthy Dkr1.11bn (Dollars 181m), an indication
of the successful merger of 1989 that brought Novo and Nordisk Gentofte
together.
While corporate Denmark flourished in 1991, Norway's companies stagnated in
an economy over-dependent for its growth on the level of oil and gas prices
but with severe mainland structural problems and a banking crisis that
worsened dramatically during the year. As a result the stock market was in a
jittery and depressed mood for most of the year, reflected in its generally
low market capitalisation figures.
There were six Norwegian-based companies listed in the FT500, all of them
the same as in 1990. But only two - the pharmaceutical company Hafslund
Nycomed and Saga Petroleum - improved their relative standing in the table
rising from 286th to 227th and from 272th to 241st respectively. The others
fell down the table. The paper products group Orkla Borregaard declined to
463rd place from 411 while Bergesen dy group, the shipowners, fell back to
323rd position from 281.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
