<PROFILE>_AN-CAMBUAAIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (10): A new Incentive for growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INCENTIVE is a newcomer, in 232nd place, to this year's FT500. It is a
highly diverse Swedish industrial and investment group which was floated on
the Stockholm bourse last July for the first time after its creation out of
Asea's Swedish holdings independent of the Swedish-Swiss engineering giant
Asea Brown Boveri.
Mr Mikael Lilius, chief executive and president, has been given a clear
remit by the company's dominant Wallenberg owners - to transform Incentive
into an industrial company with its core activities based in engineering.
'We must have new habits, new traditions and a new culture,' he explains,
keen to assert that the name may be the same but the new Incentive will be
different from the old one, though even the company's own employees have
trouble understanding this.
Mr Lilius is in his element in transforming industrial companies. Before
being hand-picked for the top post by Mr Curt Nicolin, the legendary
lieutenant of the Wallenberg empire and Incentive's chairman, Mr Lilius
worked for Huhtamaki, the Finnish company, where he pushed through an
important restructuring of its activities.
His strategy for Incentive has been spelt out for everybody to appreciate.
As many as seven companies in the old Incentive group with total sales of
Skr7bn (Dollars 1.2bn) and accounting for around a quarter of its profits
are to be sold off. These include Orrefors, the high quality glassware
concern; Gense, specialists in the design and manufacture of table utensils;
and AKA the maker of environmental niche products.
'Some of our best activities are being divested,' admits Mr Lilius. 'But
these do not fit into our core strategy.' But he is in no hurry to
relinquish them and believes it will take up to two years to complete their
sale.
At the same time Incentive's remaining operations are to be concentrated in
five designated business areas - transportation; construction and
environment; materials handling; process industries; and the world famous
photographic concern, Hasselblad.
'We are strong, with total revenues of around SKr10bn,' asserts Mr Lilius.
'We are therefore in a position to grow now in our core products without
taking any major risks. You could say at the moment we have more money than
good ideas for expansion.' Although highly confident about Sweden's
industrial future once the recession is over, he believes Incentive's growth
will take place mainly abroad through acquisitions and direct production.
But the company is not going to be exclusively industrial even after the
completion of its core strategy. From a capitalisation viewpoint,
Incentive's investment portfolio will remain important. Of its shareholder's
equity capital totalling SKr17bn, as much as SKr12.5bn is at present derived
from its stock. In the first half of 1991, 70 per cent of the company's
SKr671m profits was earned from its share-holdings.
Incentive will remain the dominant share owner in Asea, where it holds 25
per cent of voting rights and share capital, in Electrolux with 48 per cent
of voting rights and 11 per cent equity, and in the world's biggest welding
company Esab, with 49 per cent voting rights and 44 per cent share capital.
Mr Lilius hopes Incentive's own industrial activities will account for an
increasingly larger part of its earnings in the future. By the mid 1990s the
company could become another aggressive Swedish player on the wider European
stage, further proof that the Wallenberg empire is not going to fall apart
in the face of increasing corporate challenges.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-15091</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CAMBUAAHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (8): Uncertainty constrains
performances - Italy / Share prices reflected adverse internal factors and
poor economic conditions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS INVESTORS and stockbrokers face up to Italy's 'big bang', now getting
under way with the demise of traditional stockbrokers, the birth of
securities intermediation firms and the start of continuous screen-based
trading, they can derive little satisfaction from the performance of shares
listed on the Milan market.
Activity has been racked by uncertainty over the past two years. Sentiment
has been depressed. Trading volumes have been low and share price indices
have reflected a combination of adverse internal factors and poor general
economic conditions. It is against this background that Italian
representation in the FT500 should be read.
At the end of September 1991, Milan's MIB general share index, which is
reset to 1,000 at the start of each year, stood at 1,042. However, this
modest improvement on the year's beginning was more than wiped out by
December, although the drop did not match the mauling that share prices
suffered in 1990, with the MIB general index closing at 750 on the last
trading day of the year.
The MIB performed particularly badly in the second half of 1990. After
peaking at 1,113 in mid-June, it fell sharply and gains made in 1988 and
1989 were lost. Capitalisation of shares quoted on the Milan board totalled
L168,135bn (Dollars 141bn) at year-end 1990, a drop of 21.9 per cent
compared to L215,244bn on December 31, 1989.
Share prices had already started to slide when the Gulf crisis broke in
August 1990. Iraq's invasion of Kuwait helped the downward movement that
started in July when the MIB fell by 3.1 per cent after registering advances
in four successive months. The 11.8 per cent drop in August was followed by
further falls of between 5 and 6 per cent in each of the next three months,
with 1990's low of 725 being touched on 27 November.
However, the Gulf crisis was not the only adverse factor affecting the Milan
stock market and Italian share prices in 1990 and 1991. Though long
expected, the introduction of legislation to tax capital gains also
contributed to the depressed tone.
'The taxation of gains arising from equity trading, implemented through a
decree law in autumn 1990, was a new disturbance for the Borsa. It led to
further reduction in trading levels and encouraged Italian operators to work
increasingly on foreign stock markets,' says Attilio Ventura, chairman of
the Milan stockbrokers' executive committee. He notes that after a long
wait, the market had expected the legislators to produce a much better
drafted bill.
Leading broker Paolo Azzoni considers that the Gulf crisis and the saga of
Italy's capital gains tax were only part of the reason for Milan's poor
showing. 'The capital gains tax decree affected trading volumes,' he says,
pointing to falls of 14, 11 and 16 per cent that were recorded in September,
October and November 1990.
'But prices have been hit more by economic fundamentals. By autumn 1990 many
operators were concerned that the Italian economy would not escape
recession. Lower dividend earnings were expected. In addition, Italy's
situation is aggravated by a budget deficit problem that keeps interest
rates high. Monetary policy cannot be eased to alleviate the recession,'
comments Mr Azzoni.
Already facing a severe set of negative factors, confidence in Milan's stock
market was dealt a further blow with the failure of Lombardfin. This led to
a week's delay in September 1990's settlement. Earlier that year, the
failure of Commissionaria Oggioni had held up March's settlement for 10
days. More recently, the difficulties of two brokers and Commissionaria
Misafin caused the August 30, 1991 settlement to slip to September 10.
Movements in the prices of leading industrial stocks reflected an
increasingly gloomy business climate in 1990 and a worsening in 1991.
Turin-based Fiat, Italy's largest private sector corporation, has suffered
badly. With more than half of turnover generated by automobile sales and
approximately a further quarter from buses, trucks and components, Fiat is
vulnerable to downturns in these sectors.
A combination of erosion of domestic market share by imported cars and
fiercely competitive international markets hit Fiat. Its net revenues from
automobiles declined in 1990 and operating profit in this sector slumped by
nearly two thirds. With prospects giving no cause for optimism, the price of
Fiat ordinary shares fell by more than one half in 1990, dropping from
L11,135 to L5,351. At the end of September 1991, Fiat's shares stood at
L5,200. Its FT500 ranking has plummeted; from 15th place Fiat falls to 53rd.
Office automation equipment maker Olivetti, another prestigious name and
industrial blue chip on the Milan board feeling the effects of the worldwide
crisis in the computer industry, has suffered an equally sharp setback.
Starting 1990 at L7,415, the price of Olivetti ordinary shares lost 57 per
cent to finish at L3,220. The decline in 1991 took the price to L2,920 at
September 30. Olivetti's place in the FT500 rankings falls from 178 to 375.
Olivetti chief Carlo de Benedetti experienced similar disappointments
elsewhere in his business empire. The price of shares in Compagnie
Industriali Riunite (CIR) crashed from L4,970 to L2,512 in 1990, slipping
further to L2,285 at the end of September 1991. CIR's FT500 ranking drops
from 207 to 435, while Cofide falls out of the list.
Pirelli and Company also left the FT500, having previously been ranked at
363. In common with its sister company and other Italian industrials, shares
in Pirelli SpA took a beating in 1990. But Pirelli SpA stays in the
rankings, though at 362 it is significantly lower than the previous year's
257.
Shares in Italy's financial sector and utilities generally fared somewhat
better than industrials, but have nevertheless received harsh treatment.
The price of shares in Generali Assicurazioni, the Trieste insurer which is
the country's most capitalised corporation and heads Italy's presence in the
FT500, started 1990 at L33,151, rose to a maximum of L41,000 and then fell
sharply to L27,400 at year-end. The fall continued in 1991, and the price
stood at L25,800 at the end of September. Generali slips from 12th place to
24th in the FT500.
Performance of bank shares reflected the dull business environment.
Shareholders in merchant bank Mediobanca saw the value of their investments
decline significantly during 1990, as the price of shares dropped by 28 per
cent from L18,500 on the first day of trading to L13,260 at year-end. Though
the price recovered to L15,020 at the end of September 1991, Mediobanca's
place in the FT500 slips from 73 to 117. Leading retail bank Banca
Commerciale Italiana also lost ground and its FT500 ranking drops from 133
to 166.
The prices of most quoted companies were down in 1990, and there was little
progress in the first nine months of 1991. With the MIB index recording an
overall retreat that compares unfavourably with other main European markets,
the FT500 consequently registers a decline in the placings of Italian
companies. Excluding eight newcomers, only four Italian companies improve
their positions, while 22 fall back.
How does Italy stand in the rankings? Taking into consideration the seven
companies that slipped from the list, its representation remained at 33.
Clearly the number of ranked quoted companies remains anomalously small for
a leading European country. Italy has no companies in the top 10 and, with
Generali Assicurazioni the largest at 24th place, only one in the top 50. In
the new rankings only three Italian companies appear in the top 100, against
five previously.
There were no significant changes over the year, and the features that
characterised the Milan stock market and Italy's presence in the FT500 12
months ago remain. With only 220 quoted companies, the Borsa lacks depth. It
is also incestuous, with numerous companies interlinked through
cross-holdings, and dominated by a few family groups and state-controlled
companies.
It is estimated that there are several hundred companies whose shares are
suitable for quotation. But even where cultural difficulties concerning
family ownership and management are overcome, potential newcomers are
deterred by the market's volatility and poor reputation.
The Borsa is small and, as the FT500 clearly reveals, the companies quoted
on it are themselves small when measured against a continental scale. This
year's FT500 reflects poor performance of the Milan index relative to share
price indices in other European markets. But, beyond this, the rankings show
that building globally-sized companies is proving hard for Italian business.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
