<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (7): Acquisitions give companies a
lift - France / The leaders in Europe's third largest stock market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE'S top quoted companies have continued their steady march up the FT500
league, partly reflecting their position as some of the busiest acquirers in
Europe, in some cases leading the concentration of their industrial sector.
In part, they were also helped by the relatively strong performance of the
French stock market in 1991, which led to an overall performance between the
two FT500 cut-off points that outstripped rival markets, notably Germany and
Italy.
By the end of October, the French main market included 556 domestically
incorporated companies, down from 578 a year previously and 229 foreign
listings, up slightly from 226 at the end of October 1990, according to the
Societe des Bourses Francaises.
It is Europe's third largest stock market with a capitalisation of
FFr1,879bn (Dollars 340bn). However, it is still small in relation to the
size of the French economy and the market in many of the top companies'
shares can be very limited due to the often large stakes - so called noyaux
durs - held by loyal shareholders.
On the takeover front, British companies were the biggest European buyers
abroad in 1990, according to a recent study by KPMG, the accounting group,
but the French slipped into the lead in the first nine months of 1991. They
spent Dollars 5.9bn abroad in the nine months to September, Dollars 1bn more
than their British counterparts, says KPMG.
Among the most notable cross-border deals are the FFr12.5bn unsolicited
takeover of Square D, the US electrical distribution group, by Schneider,
the French electrical equipment company, and the FFr3.8bn takeover of the
transmission equipment division of Rockwell International by Alcatel
Alsthom, the telecommunications and engineering giant. Also falling into the
period covered by the FT500 is the partial merger of Sanofi, the
pharmaceuticals subsidiary of oil group Elf Aquitaine, with Sterling Drug of
the US.
In two of these three case, these deals have been reflected in a further
rise in the buyers' rankings. Elf rose seven places to take 13th position,
where it consolidates its position as the largest French quoted company in
the FT 500, with its market capitalisation of Dollars 17.4bn, also
reflecting a strong profits performance.
It is followed by Alcatel, which changed its name during the period from the
unwieldy Compagnie Generale d'Electricite, and moved up four places to 23rd.
Schneider, by contrast, tumbled from 196th to 269th, a reflection of the
continuing impact of economic downturn on its construction and engineering
subsidiaries.
France was relatively late in joining the buoyant acquisition markets of the
late 1980s, but has made up for it with a hectic burst of activity which has
started to show through in a growing internationalisation of the French
economy. Just over 40 per cent of the staff of France's 10 top companies now
works abroad, and five of the top 10 make more than half of their sales
outside France, according to a recent survey by the Direction de Relations
Economiques Exterieures.
These include Michelin, the world's largest tyre maker, which climbed from
267th to the 210th slot, reflecting the surge in its share price as it began
to digest its 1989 takeover of Uniroyal Goodrich, the US tyre group, and as
the market began to accept that Michelin was prepared to take an axe to its
own and Uniroyal's costs.
There is also Thomson-CSF, the state-controlled defence electronics group
which has climbed from 209 to 164, and has made a whole range of
partnerships with other European defence suppliers. Saint-Gobain, the glass
and pipes concern which last year bought Norton, the US abrasives group, has
had less luck, down from 65th position to 79th, reflecting the drop in
earnings and share price cause by the fall in demand in the building,
automotive and industrial supplies businesses.
The big change in this year's French listings in the FT500 is the inclusion
for the first time of companies which have at least 25 per cent of their
shares in the hands of the public. Ther previous cut-off point - 30 per cent
 -had excluded most of the state sector, with the three exceptions of Elf,
Total, the other state-controlled oil group, and Thomson-CSF. The change
reveals the real importance of French state industry.
It also coincides with the government's decision to allow sales of minority
stakes to private investors, so putting an end to President Francois
Mitterrand's freeze on privatisations and nationalisations. So there could
well be new entrants from the French state sector next year.
Now the original trio is joined by the three state insurance companies:
Union des Assurances de Paris (UAP), which comes in at 52, with a market
capitalisation of Dollars 7.7bn; Groupe des Assurances Nationales (GAN)
(63rd); and Assurances Generales de France (AGF) which makes its debut at
95. The other important new face from the state sector is Pechiney
International, the 75 per cent subsidiary of Pechiney, the state-controlled
aluminium and packaging group, which comes in at 220.
In the private sector, some of France's best known names have continued to
climb the ladder, in sectors which have shown comparative resilience to the
economic slowdown. They include LVMH the luxury goods group, up from 34th to
25th, where it is the third largest French company, followed by BSN, the
leading foods company, up from 47th to 39th.
Other reshuffles in the domestic rankings reflect takeovers and mergers,
like the link-up between Lyonnaise des Eaux, the water distribution group
and construction company Dumez, which jointly weigh in this year at number
110, or - on a smaller scale - the Pinault timber and paper group's takeover
of Conforama, France's largest furniture retailing chain.
Since the FT500 lists closed, Pinault (416th), has bid for Au Printemps, the
department store at 410. The two-thirds bid was controversial, but received
clearance from French stock exchange authorities, in spite of minority
shareholders' allegations that they were not being treated fairly. So
Pinault can be expected to climb a few more rungs this year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
