<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (3): Figuring out the differences -
The quality of corporate data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANYONE trying to analyse the accounts of companies in the different
countries across Europe should be issued with a strong government health
warning: attempts to make comparisons are likely to cause severe headaches.
As the deadline for the single European market approaches at the end of this
year, one issue still sorely lacking in standardisation is financial
reporting. Users of accounts face enormous variations in the disclosure and
treatment of information.
A survey published at the end of 1991 by the US-based Centre for
International Financial Analysis and Research (CIFAR) concluded solemnly:
'In spite of worldwide efforts . . . to harmonise financial reporting
practices, the form and substance of published annual reports varies
significantly.'
CIFAR rated the accounts of 1,000 leading companies in 44 countries by the
presence or absence of 90 items classified under seven headings: disclosure
of general information, income statements, balance sheets, funds flow
statements, accounting policies, stockholders' information and special
items.
The resulting 'international financial reporting index' ranks the non-EC
countries of Scandinavia above many of their EC counterparts. Sweden scored
highest of all, followed by Singapore and the UK. At the lower end of the
scale, Austria ranked 31, Luxembourg 38 and Portugal 42.
The same pattern emerges from individual companies. Ericsson of Sweden has
the highest overall index score, followed by the Bank of Scotland, Shell
Canada and Union Bank of Finland. Swedish businesses comprise five of the
top 10 industrial scores, while those in the UK have four of the top seven
among companies in the financial sector.
The small number of large companies in some of the countries covered may
well introduce distortions which make the index unrepresentative. However,
the general findings are borne out by other recent pieces of research as
well as more general anecdotes.
A report just produced for the European Federation of Accountants (FEE), for
example, showed wide divergence in topics such as the flow-of-funds
statement, the treatment of assets for valuation and disclosure of pension
provisions.
Mr Scott Cormack, managing partner of KPMG Peat Marwick's European Business
Centre in Brussels, says some of the principal issues treated in different
ways across borders which will need to be addressed in the future include
accounting for goodwill, foreign currency translations and tax accounting.
Many of the variations reflect the fact that accounts produced in different
countries are intended to serve different audiences. In the UK, the aim is
to provide a 'true and fair view' for investors. Elsewhere, it is often the
tax authorities that hold most sway.
Mr Cormack distinguishes two basic styles. The 'Anglo-Saxon' philosophy
stresses the profit and loss account, especially dividends and earnings,
since it is driven by short-term returns. The alternative, which is
prevalent in countries such as France and Germany, focuses on the balance
sheet. This reflects a longer-term view from more stable financiers and
others that companies should build up wealth.
In the UK, the semi-independent Accounting Standards Board, whose members
are drawn primarily from the accountancy firms, is taking a strong line in
developing new guidelines in the former mould. Elsewhere, the regulator is
often the national legislature with an eye firmly on tax revenues.
Nevertheless, there has been considerable convergence in financial reporting
in Europe over the past few years. Partly, Mr David Cairns,
secretary-general of the International Accounting Standards Committee,
argues, this is a function of the increasing search for international
capital, which has helped boost Anglo-Saxon-style reporting. Many companies
now produce two sets of accounts: one to meet local requirements and the
other for international consumption.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
