<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JAN 92 / The FT European Top 500 (1): UK companies are the big
winners - The absence, this year, of the currency factor means that moves up
and down the rankings are more 'genuine' than ever before
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIS year's FT500 is a historic one: by its date of compilation, September
30, 1991, almost all the big European economies were linked by formal or de
facto membership of the Exchange Rate Mechanism of the European Monetary
System.
So for the first time in the FT500's history, the factors which decide
whether companies move up and down the rankings largely exclude the currency
factor which has been such an overwhelming influence in the past.
The FT500 ranks companies by stock market value (that is, shares outstanding
times share price). It therefore avoids the differences between national
accounting standards that bedevil rankings based on profitability; and
avoids the inconsistencies between industries that bedevil rankings by
revenues.
Of course, such a listing can only include publicly-quoted companies. Those
economies where there are many large privately-owned industrial empires
(such as Germany) or those where the state controls significant corporate
power (such as France or Italy) are under-represented. The FT500 is a
snapshot of the relative values investors put on Europe's big
publicly-traded companies - rather than an overview of industry as a whole.
The absence, this year, of the currency factor means that moves up and down
the rankings are more 'genuine' than ever before: they represent true
changes in the values attached to individual companies' businesses rather
than the pattern of exchange rates at the moment the survey was taken.
No individual company is ever able to throw off the influence of its
domestic stock market. Thus, in a snapshot taken as the UK market reached a
peak in September this year, UK companies are the big winners at the very
top of the list. In this year's top 10, for example, Glaxo and British Gas
all move up in ranking, as does the partly-British Unilever.
Another Anglo-Dutch company, Royal Dutch/Shell handsomely retains its lead
at the top of the rankings. It is not surprising that Anglo-Dutch companies
did well: the UK (with the FT-SE index up 10.4 per cent in the period since
the last FT500 cut-off date at the end of June 1990) and the Netherlands
(where the market index was up 3.4 per cent) were the only two of the
leading European markets to show a rise. Others fell, some sharply: Italy
was down 28.5 per cent, Germany 14.5 per cent and France down 7.6 per cent.
The 15-month period used on this occasion reflects the desire to make the
FT500 more up to date at the time of publication. Stock market performances
during the period contrast markedly with the results in the 12 months to
September 1991 shown above.
Nonetheless, the rise from 10th to third in the rankings of Glaxo Holdings
of the UK represents a significant shift in the market's valuation of the
company itself.
In Italy, the weakest major stock market during the period, the biggest
casualties included two of the country's biggest industrial stocks, Olivetti
(down in rank from 178 to 375) and Compagnie Industriali Riunite (down from
207 to 435). They have another factor in common: they are both run by Carlo
De Benedetti, the Italian entrepreneur, whose magic touch has deserted him
for the moment.
In last year's FT500, the big news was the way in which German companies had
at last started to use takeovers as a way to gain size and climb up the
rankings. This time, German takeovers were again in the news. Germany has
yet to see a successful hostile takeover bid, but 1991's developments
demonstrated a variation: the hostile but ostensibly 'friendly' takeover
bid.
Pirelli's attempt to push Continental, the German tyre-maker, into a merger
was clearly failing before the end of the FT500's cut-off period. The
performance of the various Pirelli entities in the FT500 - Pirelli
Internationale fell from 269 to 333 in the ranking, and Pirelli SpA fell
from to 257 to 362 - was an augury of Pirelli's decision to abandon the bid
last December.
Of those industry sectors which contain more than a handful of companies,
four in particular stand out for strong performance. The 10 diversified
manufacturing companies which featured in this ranking and last year's rose
an average of 44 places; the 10 drugs companies rose 24 places on average;
the 16 food processing companies rose 11 places; and the 22 electricity and
water utilities (a sector with a heavy UK bias) rose six places on average.
The biggest loser among sizeable sectors was diversified holding companies,
a group with 28 members and an average drop in the rankings of 39 places.
Other poor performers were the 20 building materials companies, which
dropped 29 places on average.
State-owned companies that have 25 per cent of their shares in the hands of
the public are now eligible for inclusion in the FT500, a change from the
previously required figure of 30 per cent. This brings a number of big
French groups into the rankings, such as the French insurer UAP (ranked 52).
Austria's state oil company OeMV comes in at 288 and in Germany, Lufthansa
comes in at 188.
A similar change of ruling applies to subsidiaries of big groups as long as
25 per cent of stock is in the hands of outside shareholders. Thus Allianz
Lebensversicherung, the life insurance arm of the bigger Allianz Holding
group (ranked 6th) comes in at 104. One of Sweden's key Wallenberg holding
companies, Incentive, joins at 232. Gemina, the Fiat-controlled financial
services group, comes in at 286. Other joiners include the TF1 television
channel in France (348), controlled by the Bouygues construction group;
Italy's family-controlled property group Italmobiliare (107); and the UK
electricity utilities, privatised during the period.
Some companies joined by virtue of growth: Sims Food Group, a little-known
but rapidly growing British meat supplier, came in at 330. Two companies
still in a nascent state, Eurotunnel and Euro Disneyland, both did well.
Euro Disneyland, which opens this spring, rose from 159 to 121, and is
valued at nearly Dollars 4bn.
There were a number of other notable performances. The list of big gainers
was dominated by UK companies, including the specialist materials group
Courtaulds, which rose more than 50 places (from 205 to 152) in spite of the
recession. Willis Corroon, the insurance broker formed by a merger between
the UK's Willis Faber and the US's Corroon &amp; Black, rose from 431 to 224. A
few of the biggest losers were also British. Asda, the food retailer,
dropped from 217 to 461. Racal Electronics dropped from 96 to 351, thanks to
demerger of its Vodafone cellular phone subsidiary, which joined the
rankings at 65.
As in earlier years, a number of famous names disappeared from the list.
Swiss chocolate-maker Jacobs Suchard (formerly 125th) has dropped from the
rankings after its takeover by Philip Morris.
Italy's Montedison has left and come back again: the original company,
formerly ranked 140th, was merged into Ferruzzi Agricola Finanziaria. That
company then changed its name, to Montedison, and is ranked 231.
There were two notable disappearances in the UK. STC, formerly number 202,
sold its ICL subsidiary to Fujitsu in November 1990 then sold itself to
Canada's Northern Telecom and vanished from the rankings. And Polly Peck
International, which was ranked as high as 158th in last year's lists, is
now in administration, with its shares suspended.
