<HEADLINE>
FT  11 JAN 92 / US jobless figure hits highest level in five years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush returned to Washington from his Asian trip yesterday
to be greeted by a jump in unemployment to the highest level for five years.
Furthermore, a New York Times/CBS opinion poll showed that eight in 10
Americans believe the economy is in 'bad shape'.
The Labor Department said the unemployment rate had risen to 7.1 per cent
last month compared with 6.9 per cent in November and 5.3 per cent at the
start of the recession 18 months ago.
Financial markets took the jobs statistics calmly, although share prices
were set back - albeit fairly modestly - for the first time since
mid-December.
The deparment's figures for payroll employment were better than feared but
it revised downwards its estimate for November to show an even larger
decline - 265,000 rather than 241,000.
Speaking at Andrews air force base, Mr Bush said he was 'disappointed' by
the rise in unemployment but claimed his efforts to open markets in Asia
would stimulate growth and create more US jobs.
The opinion poll, however, indicated that fewer than a third of Americans
believed Mr Bush's Asian trip would create jobs. Mr Bush's overall approval
rating fell from 51 per cent to 48 per cent. Voters appeared evenly divided
when offered a choice of re-electing Mr Bush or supporting an unspecified
Democrat.
Mr Bush is expected to attempt to rebuild his popularity by unveiling an
ambitious growth plan in his State of the Union address on January 28.
Yesterday Mr Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve chairman, said economic data
did not support the degree of gloom expressed. The economy was stalled
rather than falling sharply. The unemployment rate remained low by the
standards of previous downturns.
The Fed would take whatever steps were needed to ensure 'sustainable
economic expansion', he said, but warned Congress that fiscal measures to
stimulate the economy were 'premature'.
